%S A390187 0,1,3,5,7,10,13,17,20,25,30,33,39,44,50,56,63,70,77
%N A390187 Minimum number of distinct consecutive sums of a permutation of [n].
%C A390187 The corresponding maximum number is A389241(n).
%H A390187 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/34">Problem 34</a>, Erdős Problems.
%H A390187 Erdős problems database contributors, <a href="https://github.com/teorth/erdosproblems/issues/95">Issue #95</a> linking Erdős problems to the OEIS.
%H A390187 Jakub Konieczny, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.07156">On consecutive sums in permutations</a>, arXiv:1504.07156 [math.CO], 2015-2021.
%e A390187 For n=5, {3, 4, 1, 2, 5} is a permutation having 10 distinct consecutive sums, namely 1, 2, 3=1+2, 4, 5=4+1, 3+4=4+1+2=2+5, 3+4+1=1+2+5, 3+4+1+2, 4+1+2+5, and 3+4+1+2+5.
%e A390187 For n=8, {7, 6, 2, 1, 4, 3, 5, 8} and its reversal are the unique permutations that have 20 distinct consecutive sums.
%t A390187 a[n_] := Min[CountDistinct[Total/@Subsequences[#,{1,\[Infinity]}]]&/@Permutations[Range[n]]]; Array[a,6,0]
